Linear regression models for evaluating the financial Performance of Pension Fund in Nigeria

Introduction:

This study seeks to examine the effect of pension fund features such as density contribution, idle contribution, number of retirement savings account membership, expenditures, Fund Size, and Age of Fund, on the Financial performance of pension funds in Nigeria. The pension scheme currently operated in Nigeria requires all employees by law to maintain a Retirement Savings Account with any Pension Fund Administrator (PFA) of their choice, the financial performance of this RSA Fund managed by the PFA is our concern here. The measure for financial Performance used in this analysis includes the Investment Income, profit before tax and Total income or Gross revenue.

Age of Fund: This refers is how long the fund has existed. In this case, the age of the pension fund and the age of the Pension Fund Administrator are the same. Penson Fund are expected to be more profitable as their existence grow. In his research, Tijjani (2014) found that a pension fund administrators financial sustainability is projected to increase with age. Ajibade et al. (2018) in his work established that Age of fund has a significant positive effect on financial performance measured by Unit Price.

Density of contribution: This refers to the total pension contribution received by the pension fund. By law, the employers and employees are expected to contribute 10% and 8% respectively in Nigeria. In Kigen (2016), researchs it was established that the contribution has a positive significant regression coefficient in predicting the financial performance of pension funds. This result however contradicts the outcome of Ajibade et al. (2018) research that suggest that contribution has a significant negative effect on financial performance and Oluoch (2013) study which suggests that the variable contribution is not a significant factor.

Idle contribution: This relates to the contributions made by the Pension funds beneficiaries that have not been put to use, that is, earning no interest or other form of investment income as a result. While it is important to ensure that optimal cash is available for liquidity needs, such as meeting obligations to retirees, having huge amount of idle fund may not be considered a good investment strategy. Ajibade et al. (2018) suggest in their study that idle contribution has a significant and positive effect on the financial Performance of pension fund.

Number of Retirement Savings Account membership: This variable is explained simply as the number of registered members of the pension scheme. Although this number is increasing over the years, there is still a huge shortfall in comparison to the number of working age population, and this can be associated with high unemployment rate faced in Nigeria amongst other things. This variable has been considered by Kigen (2016) in his research, and he suggest that it is has no significant relationship with the performance of pension funds.

Fund size: This variable was represented by Net Pension Asset Under Management. According to studies (Gallagher and Martin 2005), a pension funds performance improves as it grows in size. The outcome of Kigen (2016) study shows that fund size has a negative and significant relationship with the financial performance of pension funds. While the result of Oluoch (2013) shows that there is no significant relationship between the asset and financial performance of pension fund.

Expenditure: In this study expenditure is represented by Asset based Fees and Vat. According to Tijjani (2014), Pension Fund Administrators must make sure that their income always exceeds their expenses in order to retain strong financial standing throughout time. In the studies of Kigen (2016), administrative expenditure has a positive significance influence over financial performance of pension funds. This is contrary to the work of Ajibade et al. (2018) where it was established that this variable has no significant effect.

Initial trail (IT) Models:

Due to the dearth of data, initial data collection and analysis process for the various variables was centered around the cumulative values for all Pension fund Administrators for each year from 2012 to 2021, which implies that we only have 10years observations, and the defined variables below were used. This data collection style is similar to that used in the study carry out by Oluoch (2013).

Definition of Variables Definition of Variables
Dependent Varible Investment income (Inv.Inc)
Dependent Varible Fund Size (AUM)
Independent Varible Density of COntribuitons (DC)
Independent Varible Expenditure (EXPF)
Independent Varible Retirement Savings Account Memebership (RSAM)

IT_MODEL Version 1: Where the dependent variable is measured as investment income, derived as an aggregate of Interest/Coupons, Dividends and Net unrealized Gains/(Losses) on quoted equities / equity funds for all PFA during each year; and independent variables includes EXPF, DC, and RSAM, derived as relative values, that is the values recorded during each year.

Second trial (ST) Models:

Given the limited observations (10-15 oberservations) we have in the initial models, it became necessary to find a better alternative that would produce substantial number of obersavations and therefore, the value of each Pension Fund Administrators Per year was introduced as an individual obervation and new sets of regression was rerun on this data. This approach is similar to the study carried out by Ajibade et al. (2018).

CATEGORIES OF VARIABLES Variable Names
Dependent Varible Profit before Tax (PBT)
Dependent Varible Investment income (Inc)
Independent Varible Net Pension Fund Asset Under Management (AUM)
Independent Varible Density of COntribuitons (DC)
Independent Varible Retirement Savings Account Memebership (RSAM)
Independent Varible Idle Contributions (Idle)
Independent Varible Age of Fund (AOF)
